rature tempered romantic love with the claims of family and community, and treated the rules of gender complementarity as comedic fodder. Twentieth-century Jewish writers turned back to tradition, finding pleasures in matchmaking, intergenerational ties, and sexual segregation. In the modern Jewish voices of Sigmund Freud, Erica Jong, Philip Roth, and Tony Kushner, the Jewish heretical challenge to the European romantic sublime has become the central sexual ideology of our time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aJewish literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aJewish literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aJewish marriage customs and ritesxHistory. 0aLove in literature. 0aMarriage customs and rites in literature. 0aSex in literature. 4aHaskalah. 4aJewish literature. 4aarranged marriage. 4acourtship. 4agender complementarity. 4akinship. 4aromance. 4asecularization. 4asexuality. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Jewish.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070397940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080479962140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804799621423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804799621.jpg  a978-3-11-070397-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles